</md></sn><sn><md>#### Merging the Ideal Transaction In Self

I have never intentionally engaged in a bad transaction in my life. I always carry a fear of Allah that if I hurt or wrong someone, I may be held accountable for it. However, there have been times when others have taken advantage of me.

I place myself at **Level A**, because I do not cheat others. My main challenge is not preventing myself from cheating, but protecting myself from being cheated. Honesty is already a built-in part of my personality; therefore, my focus should be on improving awareness, judgment, and caution.

#### Individual Transactions

In individual transactions, my closest relatives—such as my mother and some of my aunts—usually deal with me fairly. However, many others do not. If even relatives can sometimes fail to maintain fair transactions, then the outside world requires even greater caution.

Therefore, I must be more careful in my dealings and remain strict in following my transaction rules.

#### Group Transactions

My performance in group transactions has been poor. I often become the first person to pay the bill. Sometimes people ask me to pay on their behalf, and later I feel embarrassed to ask for the money back.

This is an area where I need improvement. Before entering a group transaction, I should either become the master who collects money first or avoid the transaction and act independently.

#### Lending Money

When it comes to borrowing money, I rarely borrow from others. If I do, I try to repay it as quickly as possible, often within a short time. By the grace of Allah, I have been able to maintain this habit.

Lending money to someone can be a good moral act and a form of helping others. However, lending should be based on the importance of the need and the trustworthiness of the person. Compassion should be balanced with wisdom and caution.
